CONTRACT DEFINITION:
1. RESEARCH NOTE: See architecture/issue3-4-metadata-and-exports.md (Issue 4 section). registerDefaultHarnesses is exported ONLY from src/harnesses/index.ts (line 21), NOT from the public src/index.ts. Its body (src/harnesses/register-defaults.ts L28-48) registers 'claude-code' + 'pi' idempotently (guarded by registry.has(id)). HarnessRegistry.getInstance() (harness-registry.ts) starts EMPTY — no lazy auto-registration. There are ZERO production callers (only tests + JSDoc). PRP P2M1T1S2 previously kept it OUT of the public barrel and forbade import-time auto-invocation to avoid test pollution — but that earlier decision is what produced the documented bug (example 02 / new Agent({model}) fail). THIS bugfix PRD supersedes it: the Expected Behavior (h3.3) is 'a convenient way to register both built-in harnesses, OR auto-registration, so users do not have to hand-register.' Implement BOTH safety nets, but in a test-safe way.
2. INPUT: registerDefaultHarnesses(registry = HarnessRegistry.getInstance()) from register-defaults.ts. The function is idempotent (has() guards). HarnessRegistry has: getInstance() (L166), register(provider) (L193, throws on duplicate), get(id) (L221), has(id) (L90), _resetForTesting().
3. LOGIC: (a) PUBLIC EXPORT — add `export { registerDefaultHarnesses } from './harnesses/index.js';` (or the specific './harnesses/register-defaults.js') to src/index.ts in the existing harness-configuration export block. (b) LAZY AUTO-REGISTRATION — implement the most test-safe option: in src/core/agent.ts constructor, AFTER computing effectiveHarness and BEFORE/AROUND the `registry.get(effectiveHarness)` lookup (current lines 125-129), if the lookup returns undefined AND effectiveHarness is a built-in default id ('pi' or 'claude-code'), call registerDefaultHarnesses(registry) once and retry the lookup. This is minimal and targeted: it only materializes defaults when an Agent actually needs a default harness that is missing, and the idempotency guard means it never overwrites a mock a test has already registered. Do NOT call registerDefaultHarnesses() unconditionally at module import time (test pollution). Do NOT modify HarnessRegistry.getInstance() to auto-register (too broad — called everywhere). Pseudocode:
   ```
   let harnessInstance = registry.get(effectiveHarness);
   if (!harnessInstance && (effectiveHarness === 'pi' || effectiveHarness === 'claude-code')) {
     registerDefaultHarnesses(registry);   // idempotent; skips already-registered ids
     harnessInstance = registry.get(effectiveHarness);
   }
   if (!harnessInstance) throw new Error(`Harness '${effectiveHarness}' is not registered`);
   ```
   Apply the SAME safety net in stream() and executePrompt() if those paths also do registry.get() (verify via grep; mirror the constructor logic). Import registerDefaultHarnesses from '../harnesses/register-defaults.js' (or via the harnesses barrel) in agent.ts.
4. OUTPUT: src/index.ts re-exports registerDefaultHarnesses (grep confirms it). new Agent({model}) with NO configureHarnesses and NO manual registration resolves to a real 'pi' harness without throwing. registerDefaultHarnesses is now a documented public symbol. npm run lint + npm test green.
5. MOCKING/ISOLATION: Verify existing tests that do HarnessRegistry._resetForTesting() then register their own mocks are NOT broken by the lazy auto-register — because the has() guard skips already-registered ids, and auto-register only triggers when the resolved harness is missing. Add/confirm a test isolation assertion if needed.
